The Ministry of
Health on Tuesday announced confirmation of 117 new COVID-19 cases
in the country from a sample
size of 2,632 tested in the last 24 hours, marking an increase in the
positivity rate to 4.4 percent. Of the cases, 70
are Kenyans while 47 are foreigners; 68 are males and 49 are females, while the
youngest is a two-year-old and the oldest is 82 years old. Total confirmed
positive cases are now 324,976 and cumulative tests so far conducted are
3,670,179. The cases were
recorded in three counties, namely; Nairobi 74, Bungoma 17, Kitui 12, Kilifi 5,
Kiambu 4, Garissa 2, Siaya 2 and Turkana had one case. Health Cabinet
Secretary Mutahi Kagwe, in a statement to newsrooms, said 81 patients recovered
from the disease, all of them from the Home-Based and Isolation Care Program.
This pushes the total recoveries to 318,605. No patient has succumbed
to the disease; therefore the cumulative fatalities remain at 5,651. “There are 4
patients currently admitted in our health facilities, while 716 are under the
Home-Based Isolation and Care program. No patient is in the Intensive Care Unit
(ICU), none is on supplemental oxygen and no patient is in the High Dependency
Unit (HDU),” noted CS Kagwe. “As of May 30, 2022,
a total of 18,204,328 vaccines have been administered across the country. Of
these, 16,460,859 are doses administered to the adult population (18 years and
above).” The CS said
1,369,449 doses were administered to those between 15 to 17 years; 34,391 are
below 15 years but above 12 years, while 339,629 are booster doses. He stated that the
total number of vaccines administered in the last 24 hours is 10,677 while the
total number of people fully vaccinated in the last 24 hours is 4,792. “Proportion of adults
fully vaccinated was 31.0%. The government is working towards vaccinating a
targeted population of 27,246,033,” noted Kagwe.